# Network: Destination-address transitions form two disconnected realms:
# 10.0.0.1--10.0.0.2 and 10.0.1.1--10.0.1.2.
# Policy: id leaves all four headers unchanged before each topology step.
# Topology: Each address pair is connected bidirectionally; there are no cross-realm transitions.
# Property within-first: The first address reaches its peer.
# Property within-second-reverse: The second realm is connected in the reverse direction.
# Property across-realms: No sequence connects the first realm to the second.
# Property broad-source: One member of the disjunctive source, 10.0.1.1, reaches 10.0.1.2.
# Property impossible-target: A destination IP cannot equal two distinct addresses simultaneously.
policy = id;
topology =
    (filter(dst_ip = 10.0.0.1) . dst_ip <- 10.0.0.2)
  + (filter(dst_ip = 10.0.0.2) . dst_ip <- 10.0.0.1)
  + (filter(dst_ip = 10.0.1.1) . dst_ip <- 10.0.1.2)
  + (filter(dst_ip = 10.0.1.2) . dst_ip <- 10.0.1.1);
check within-first: dst_ip = 10.0.0.1 => dst_ip = 10.0.0.2;
check within-second-reverse: dst_ip = 10.0.1.2 => dst_ip = 10.0.1.1;
check across-realms: dst_ip = 10.0.0.1 => dst_ip = 10.0.1.2;
check broad-source: dst_ip = 10.0.0.1 | dst_ip = 10.0.1.1 => dst_ip = 10.0.1.2;
check impossible-target: true => dst_ip = 10.0.0.1 & dst_ip = 10.0.1.2;
